# How do I play with this?

First‚Ä¶get set up on your computer. 

* If you are on a Mac, you will need a text editor and a web browser. [Follow these steps to set this up.](?tab=t.0)  
* If you are on Windows, [you can use Notepad as your text editor](?tab=t.47r9kbgpa0r8). You can also use Visual Studio if you know what that is, but it isn‚Äôt required.

After that, our recommendation is that you choose one of the three options below.

## [üç¶Vanilla: Examples of coding with AI. ](?tab=t.3hmx0rrd6ia3#heading=h.xhrwuj3qh3se) 

Watch videos embedded in the Vanilla section of the toolkit and learn how they are made. This is good for dipping your toe in and getting ideas about how this might work, but aren‚Äôt quite ready to try it yourself.

## [üç´Chocolate: Most of you will start here.](?tab=t.xu2vh2luyrdq#heading=h.xhrwuj3qh3se) 

The directions show you how to write your own prompt, enter it into AI Studio, save the code to your computer, and open the code with Chrome. You can develop your own ideas

## [üçåBanana Split: You are techy and want to push the limits of AI.](?tab=t.kxis4rw8icnv)

This section shows you how to make more advanced tools involving spreadsheets, localStorage, or use data stored externally. It also introduces you to some other tools you might find useful for building apps that go beyond just your computer.

# Evan‚Äôs Examples

Here are more examples of tools Evan has built using AI to help himself, colleagues, and his students do more.

* [Project Sidestep](https://side-step.replit.app) \- this is the app that Evan and Lisa built to help the student with difficulty inferencing. We looked at this together during the workshop. You can use this for a number of different assignments \- it is quite helpful for breaking down any task into smaller ones and simplifying the work for students. How would you use this with your students or your own work? 

![][image1]

* [Snarkyl](https://snarkyl-emwdx.replit.app) \- Evan built this as a clone of the more capable [snorkl.app](https://snorkl.app/) website that is out in the world. He wanted to answer the question of whether or not it would be possible to build an app to give students feedback on their written work through sending a picture of it to a large language model. 

![][image2]

* [Group Maker](https://evanweinberg.com/group-maker/) \- one of Evan‚Äôs first tools created using AI back in 2023\. It provides lots of options for inputting student names and randomly generating groups of various sizes. You also get options for adjusting the groups once they are made.  
* [Smart Comments](https://evanweinberg.com/smart-comments/#/) \- a comment generator and tool that allows for custom generation of comment banks with different subjects, wildcards for pronouns and names, and flexibility for reordering comments and selecting from a dropdown menu. This was Evan‚Äôs tool of choice for three of the past four report writing sessions.    
* [Student Notes](https://evanweinberg.com/student-notes/students) \- Evan created this as an anecdotal log when his school‚Äôs log entry system did not allow him to review what he had put in for specific students. You can paste in data [from this spreadsheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1JQI1v4GH83_78nHQjZHyuCmxrQZ6lHSh76wq6-cvClU/edit?gid=0#gid=0) into the Students tab, and then go over to ‚ÄòTickets‚Äô to create a ticket for a specific student.
